Another factor that contributes to this is the density of the cornea, which is the clear, protective front surface of the eye. People with blue eyes have thinner corneas compared to those with other eye colors. The cornea works to focus light entering the eye and helps to protect the sensitive retina at the back of the eye. Because the cornea is thinner in people with blue eyes, it may not effectively filter UV light as efficiently as it does for those with other eye colors.

Additionally, some research suggests that certain genes may influence the susceptibility of eye color to UV light. People with blue eyes, for example, may have a greater genetic predisposition to not having the proper pigmentation in their eyes to absorb and block UV light as effectively."
