Another notable instance of large-scale counterfeiting occurred during World War II when the Japanese military, the Japanese military or the Japanese Red Army, began producing fake US currency to finance their operations. The fake currency, known as the “Red Seal” bills, were of high quality and were used extensively in occupied territories. The Japanese were eventually caught and the counterfeiting operation was dismantled.

In the early 20th century, the Great Train Robbery, which took place in England, is another example of large-scale counterfeiting. A group of robbers stole a train carrying money and cheques from the Royal Mail Railway, and they managed to make off with over £2 million ($10 million in today's value) before being caught by the police."
