3. Keep your operating system, antivirus software, and other security programs up to date.
4. Install a firewall and ensure it is turned on.
5. Be cautious of suspicious emails, links, and downloads, and never provide personal information or login credentials in response to them.
6. Use a virtual private network (VPN) when accessing the internet from public networks or untrusted networks.
7. Regularly check your accounts for unusual activity and change your passwords if necessary.
8. Educate yourself about common cyber threats and stay informed about the latest security best practices.
9. Create complex and unique usernames and passwords for all your accounts, and avoid using the same password for multiple accounts.
10. Set up multi-factor authentication (MFA) for all your sensitive accounts.
11. Avoid using public computers or Wi-Fi networks to access personal accounts.
12. Consider using a password manager to securely store and manage your passwords.
